      description   : "4.1.17 Ensure the audit configuration is immutable"
      info          : "Set system audit so that audit rules cannot be modified with auditctl . Setting the flag \"-e 2\" forces audit to be put in immutable mode. Audit changes can only be made on system reboot. In immutable mode, unauthorized users cannot execute changes to the audit system to potentially hide malicious activity and then put the audit rules back. Users would most likely notice a system reboot and that could alert administrators of an attempt to make unauthorized audit changes."
      solution      : "Edit or create the file /etc/audit/rules.d/99-finalize.rules and add the line -e 2 at the end of the file This setting will ensure reloading the auditd config to set active settings requires a system reboot."
